# Python environment with uv

This project uses [`uv`](https://docs.astral.sh/uv/) for Python
environment, dependency, and interpreter management. **Never invoke
`python`, `pip`, `virtualenv`, `pyenv`, `poetry`, or `pipx` directly.**

For the full rules, load `@{{ ai_folder }}/instructions/python/tooling.md`.

## Common operations

| You want to | Run this |
| --- | --- |
| Create the env after a fresh clone | `uv sync` |
| Add a runtime dep | `uv add <pkg>` |
| Add a dev dep | `uv add --dev <pkg>` |
| Remove a dep | `uv remove <pkg>` |
| Run any Python command | `uv run <cmd>` (e.g. `uv run pytest`) |
| Upgrade one package | `uv lock --upgrade-package <pkg>` |
| Upgrade everything (within constraints) | `uv lock --upgrade` |
| Pin a different interpreter | edit `.python-version`, then `uv sync` |

## If a Python command needs to run

Always prefix with `uv run`:

```sh
uv run pytest
uv run ruff format .
uv run ruff check . --fix
uv run mypy src/
uv run python -m my_module
```

`uv run` verifies the lockfile and environment before invoking the
command, so you'll never hit "wrong version installed" mysteries.

## If the user asks something pip-flavoured

| User says | You do |
| --- | --- |
| "install requests" | `uv add requests` |
| "pip install -r requirements.txt" | Look for `pyproject.toml`. If found, `uv sync`. If only `requirements.txt`, migrate it: `uv add $(cat requirements.txt)`. |
| "activate the venv" | Don't. `uv run` makes activation unnecessary. |
| "create a virtualenv" | `uv sync` (it creates `.venv/` automatically). |
| "freeze the requirements" | `uv lock`. The lockfile is `uv.lock`. |

## What gets committed

- `pyproject.toml` ‚Äî yes.
- `uv.lock` ‚Äî **yes**. Always.
- `.python-version` ‚Äî yes.
- `.venv/` ‚Äî never.

## After making any dependency change

1. Run `uv sync` to make sure the environment matches the new lockfile.
2. Run `uv run pytest` to make sure nothing broke.
3. Commit `pyproject.toml` and `uv.lock` together. Never one without the
   other.

## Reporting back

After running uv operations, summarise:
- What you added/removed.
- Whether `uv.lock` changed.
- Whether the test suite still passes.
- Any deprecation warnings or resolver conflicts uv printed.
